## `crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/run/pty`

This subtree makes an `--unshare-pid`-sandboxed child behave like a normal interactive process attached to a terminal, by giving it a private PTY and relaying bytes/signals between it and the host's real tty. Depending on this module gets you one call, `run_on_pty`, returning `Ok(None)` to signal "not a tty, fall back to stdio inheritance" versus `Ok(Some(status))` for a real PTY session — callers must handle both.

`mod.rs` owns the whole session: PTY allocation, `CLOEXEC` hardening against `bwrap`'s fd-forwarding, `SIGWINCH` blocking/relay, raw-mode enter/restore via `RawGuard`, and spawning the three per-session threads (input relay, output relay, WINCH relay). `input_relay.rs` supplies just one of those three — the cancellable stdin→PTY thread — because a plain blocking `read` on stdin can't be interrupted, and a leaked relay thread will steal input from a later unrelated stdin read (e.g. `ctx-run`'s post-session prompt). `mod.rs` is the only caller of `spawn_input_relay`/`stop_input_relay`; the invariant that must hold across the boundary is that every code path out of `run_on_pty` (success, error, panic through `RawGuard`) eventually calls `stop_input_relay` before touching real stdin again — the module doesn't defend against a future change that skips this on some exit path.

The other two threads (output relay, WINCH relay) live entirely in `mod.rs` and aren't split out; the split for input relay exists specifically because its cancellation logic needed independent unit testing (self-pipe + poll), not because of a general one-thread-per-file convention. Ordering invariant spanning both files: `SIGWINCH` must be blocked before any relay thread spawns (including the input relay), so a change to spawn order in `mod.rs` can silently break resize forwarding without touching `input_relay.rs` at all.